#### Benefits

âœ… Clean separation of content and code
âœ… Built-in TypeScript types from schema
âœ… Markdown files are easy to edit
âœ… Can use MDX for interactive components
âœ… Automatic validation via Zod schema
âœ… Fast builds with Astro's optimization
âœ… Content versioning friendly
âœ… Can use VS Code markdown extensions

---

### Option 2: Markdown Files with Frontmatter (Simple)

If you don't want to use Astro Content Collections, you can manually load markdown files.

#### Structure

```
src/
  content/
    docs/
      getting-started/
        welcome.md
        connecting-accounts.md
      features/
        creating-posts.md
```

#### Implementation

**File: `src/utils/docsLoader.ts`**

```typescript
import fs from 'fs';
import path from 'path';
import matter from 'gray-matter';
import { marked } from 'marked';

export interface DocMeta {
  title: string;
  description: string;
  category: string;
  order?: number;
  tags?: string[];
  relatedSections?: string[];
}

export interface Doc {
  id: string;
  slug: string;
  meta: DocMeta;
  content: string;
  html: string;
}

export async function loadDocs(): Promise<Doc[]> {
  const docsDir = path.join(process.cwd(), 'src/content/docs');
  const docs: Doc[] = [];

  function readDocsRecursively(dir: string, category: string = '') {
    const files = fs.readdirSync(dir);

    files.forEach(file => {
      const filePath = path.join(dir, file);
      const stat = fs.statSync(filePath);

      if (stat.isDirectory()) {
        readDocsRecursively(filePath, file);
      } else if (file.endsWith('.md')) {
        const fileContent = fs.readFileSync(filePath, 'utf-8');
        const { data, content } = matter(fileContent);

        const slug = path.relative(docsDir, filePath)
          .replace(/\.md$/, '')
          .replace(/\\/g, '/');

        docs.push({
          id: slug,
          slug,
          meta: data as DocMeta,
          content,
          html: marked(content),
        });
      }
    });
  }

  readDocsRecursively(docsDir);
  return docs;
}

export async function loadDoc(slug: string): Promise<Doc | null> {
  const docs = await loadDocs();
  return docs.find(doc => doc.slug === slug) || null;
}
```

**Install dependencies:**

```bash
pnpm add gray-matter marked
```

#### Benefits

âœ… Simple to understand
âœ… No framework-specific knowledge needed
âœ… Easy to migrate to other systems
âš ï¸ Manual file loading and parsing
âš ï¸ No automatic TypeScript types

---

### Option 3: Headless CMS (External Management)

For non-technical team members or larger teams, use a headless CMS.

#### Recommended Options

**A. Sanity.io**
- Real-time collaborative editing
- Rich text editor with custom blocks
- Built-in media management
- Versioning and rollback
- Free tier available

**B. Strapi**
- Self-hosted option
- Full REST/GraphQL API
- Role-based access control
- Media library
- Open source

**C. Contentful**
- Enterprise-grade
- Multi-language support
- Content modeling
- Asset optimization

#### Implementation Example (Sanity)

**File: `src/lib/sanity.ts`**

```typescript
import { createClient } from '@sanity/client';

export const sanityClient = createClient({
  projectId: import.meta.env.SANITY_PROJECT_ID,
  dataset: 'production',
  useCdn: true,
  apiVersion: '2024-01-01',
});

export async function getDocs() {
  return sanityClient.fetch(`
    *[_type == "documentation"] | order(order asc) {
      _id,
      title,
      description,
      category,
      slug,
      content,
      tags,
      relatedSections
    }
  `);
}

export async function getDoc(slug: string) {
  return sanityClient.fetch(`
    *[_type == "documentation" && slug.current == $slug][0]
  `, { slug });
}
```

#### Benefits

âœ… Non-technical users can edit
âœ… WYSIWYG editor
âœ… Media management
âœ… Versioning/rollback
âœ… Role-based permissions
âš ï¸ Additional service dependency
âš ï¸ Potential costs at scale

---

### Option 4: Hybrid Approach (Git + CMS)

Use a Git-based CMS like **Tina.io** or **Decap CMS** (formerly Netlify CMS) that edits markdown files in your repository.

#### Benefits

âœ… Content stored in Git (version control)
âœ… Visual editor for non-technical users
âœ… No external dependencies
âœ… Open source
âœ… Deploy with your app

#### Example: Tina.io Setup

```bash
pnpm add tinacms @tinacms/cli
```

**File: `tina/config.ts`**

```typescript
import { defineConfig } from 'tinacms';

export default defineConfig({
  branch: 'main',
  clientId: process.env.TINA_CLIENT_ID,
  token: process.env.TINA_TOKEN,

  build: {
    outputFolder: 'admin',
    publicFolder: 'public',
  },

  schema: {
    collections: [
      {
        name: 'docs',
        label: 'Documentation',
        path: 'src/content/docs',
        format: 'md',
        fields: [
          {
            type: 'string',
            name: 'title',
            label: 'Title',
            required: true,
          },
          {
            type: 'string',
            name: 'description',
            label: 'Description',
            required: true,
          },
          {
            type: 'string',
            name: 'category',
            label: 'Category',
            options: ['getting-started', 'features', 'workflows', 'integrations', 'analytics', 'advanced'],
            required: true,
          },
          {
            type: 'rich-text',
            name: 'body',
            label: 'Body',
            isBody: true,
          },
        ],
      },
    ],
  },
});
```

Access the CMS at `/admin` and it edits files directly in your repo.

---

## Recommendation Summary

### Use **Astro Content Collections** if:
- You're already using Astro (you are!)
- Team is technical/comfortable with Git
- Want type safety and validation
- Need fast build times
- Want markdown/MDX support

### Use **Headless CMS** (Sanity/Strapi) if:
- Non-technical team members need to edit
- Need collaborative editing
- Want media management
- Need workflow/approval systems
- Budget allows for CMS costs

### Use **Git-based CMS** (Tina/Decap) if:
- Want visual editing for non-technical users
- Need Git-based version control
- Want self-hosted solution
- Don't want external dependencies

## Implementation Plan

**Phase 1: Start with Astro Content Collections**
1. Set up `src/content/config.ts` with schema
2. Create initial markdown docs in `src/content/docs/`
3. Update components to use `getCollection()` and `getEntry()`
4. Build out 10-15 core documentation pages

**Phase 2: Add CMS (if needed)**
1. Evaluate if non-technical editors are needed
2. If yes, add Tina.io for visual editing of the same markdown files
3. If no, continue with markdown files in Git

**Phase 3: Scale**
1. Add search functionality (Algolia DocSearch or Pagefind)
2. Add documentation versioning for API changes
3. Add multi-language support if needed
4. Analytics on popular docs

---

## Quick Start: Astro Content Collections

```bash
# 1. Install dependencies
pnpm add @astrojs/markdown-remark marked

# 2. Create content directory structure
mkdir -p src/content/docs/{getting-started,features,workflows,integrations,analytics,advanced}

# 3. Create config
touch src/content/config.ts

# 4. Create first doc
touch src/content/docs/getting-started/welcome.md

# 5. Update components to use getCollection/getEntry
```

This approach gives you the best balance of developer experience, content management, and scalability for your documentation system.

